lets add this to britton-air Nix-darwin includes a module that manages a background Linux VM using Apple's Virtualization framework. Nix treats this VM as a "remote" builder, even though it's running on your hardware.
1. Update your darwin-configuration.nix

Add these lines to your configuration to enable the VM and give it sufficient resources:
Nix

{ pkgs, ... }: {
  nix.linux-builder = {
    enable = true;
    ephemeral = true; # Wipes the VM state on restart for a clean build environment
    maxJobs = 4;
    config = {
      virtualisation = {
        darwin-builder = {
          diskSize = 40 * 1024; # 40GB
          memorySize = 8 * 1024; # 8GB
        };
        cores = 6;
      };
    };
  };

  # Essential: You must be a trusted user to delegate builds
  nix.settings.trusted-users = [ "root" "your-username" ];
}

2. Apply and Verify

    Run darwin-rebuild switch --flake ..

    Verify the service is running: sudo launchctl list org.nixos.linux-builder.

    Test a Linux build:
    Bash

    nix build --impure --expr '(with import <nixpkgs> { system = "aarch64-linux"; }; runCommand "test" {} "uname -a > $out")'
    cat result

    The output should say "Linux", even though you ran it on macOS.

